      <div set:html={`<h2 id="why-e-ink-secondary-screens-in-2026">Why E-Ink Secondary Screens Are Suddenly Everywhere in 2026</h2>
<p>Two things changed in 2026 that pushed E-Ink out of the "single-purpose Kindle" lane and into a genuine secondary-screen category. First, <strong>E-Ink Carta 1300 and Gallery 3 color panels</strong> matured &mdash; the refresh-rate gap with LCD dropped from about 1 Hz to a usable 5-10 Hz for text, and color E-Ink finally renders book covers and manga pages without the muddy look that plagued 2022-2024 hardware. Second, <strong>magnetic mounting and Android-on-E-Ink</strong> made these devices useful for things other than reading novels &mdash; phone-as-secondary-display, note-taking in meetings, RSS feeds without notifications.</p>
<p>This guide compares the three devices that define the 2026 E-Ink secondary-screen category: <strong>Xteink X4</strong> (a $179 magnetic ultra-thin reader that snaps to the back of your phone), <strong>Boox</strong> (a 7-inch Android reader line with the Google Play Store), and <strong>Kobo Libra Colour</strong> (a 7-inch color E-Ink reader with a hardware page-turn button and Kobo's locked-but-excellent native reader software).</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="what-secondary-screen-actually-means">What "Secondary Screen" Actually Means in 2026</h2>
<p>A "secondary screen" is not just a small E-Ink tablet. It's a device that lives next to your main work tool (laptop, phone, or desktop) and serves a specific low-attention task: long-form reading, RSS monitoring, distraction-free writing prompts, or simply giving your eyes a break from LCD backlight. The three use cases that matter:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Phone-pair reading</strong> &mdash; E-Ink reader that mounts to or pairs with your phone to offload long-form content (Substack, Pocket, RSS) without draining battery or pulling you into social apps.</li>
<li><strong>Desk-side reference</strong> &mdash; A 7-inch display next to your laptop that holds documentation, terminal output, or a book, refreshing at 5-10 Hz without eye strain.</li>
<li><strong>Dedicated reading</strong> &mdash; A traditional e-reader that's just a better reading device than a phone or tablet because it has physical buttons, weeks of battery life, and a sunlight-readable screen.</li>
</ol>
<p>Each of the three devices in this comparison excels at one of these patterns. None of them is "the best" at all three.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="xteink-x4-the-magnetic-phone-pair-reader">Xteink X4: The Magnetic Phone-Pair Reader</h2>
<p><a href="https://www.xteink.com/">Xteink</a> launched the X4 on June 5, 2026. The device is a 5.8-inch Carta 1300 E-Ink panel in a 4mm-thin aluminum body with a built-in MagSafe-compatible magnetic ring on the back. The pitch is simple: snap it to the back of any iPhone 12+ or MagSafe-compatible Android case, and you have a secondary reading screen that uses the phone's processing and network but displays on a battery-sipping E-Ink panel.</p>
<p><strong>Specifications:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Screen: 5.8" E-Ink Carta 1300, 300 ppi, 16 grayscale</li>
<li>Thickness: 4 mm (no battery, no SoC &mdash; it's a display only)</li>
<li>Weight: 78 g (lighter than an iPhone)</li>
<li>Connection: USB-C alt-mode display + magnetic mount</li>
<li>Price: $179 (early-bird) / $219 (retail)</li>
<li>Battery: zero (draws 0.8W from the host phone)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Strengths:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Truly pocketable &mdash; disappears in a jacket pocket next to the phone</li>
<li>Zero charging (it has no battery to charge)</li>
<li>Works with any phone app that supports external display (Kindle app, Kobo app, Pocket, even a terminal)</li>
<li>The 4mm thickness means it doesn't feel like a "case" &mdash; it's an accessory you snap on when you want to read</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Weaknesses:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Only 16 grayscale &mdash; no color E-Ink, so book covers and manga are rendered in dithered monochrome</li>
<li>USB-C alt-mode requires the host phone to support DisplayPort output (iPhone 15 Pro+, Pixel 8 Pro+, Galaxy S24+ all do)</li>
<li>No physical buttons &mdash; page turns happen on the phone or via a tap on the X4's touch layer</li>
<li>At $179, it's a luxury accessory, not a budget reader</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Substack/Pocket/long-form RSS readers who want their phone's apps to render on E-Ink for an hour at a time, then snap the panel off and go back to a normal phone.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="boox-the-android-app-ecosystem-reader">Boox: The Android-App Ecosystem Reader</h2>
<p><a href="https://onyxboox.com/">Onyx Boox</a> has been making Android E-Ink readers since 2006, and the 2026 lineup is their most refined yet. The relevant models for a secondary-screen use case are the 7-inch class: <strong>Boox Page</strong> (entry, $259), <strong>Boox Go 7</strong> (mid-range with note-taking, $349), and <strong>Boox Palma 2</strong> (phone-sized 6.13", $249). All run Boox's Android 13 fork with Google Play Store pre-installed.</p>
<p><strong>Specifications (Boox Page as the reference):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Screen: 7" E-Ink Carta 1300, 300 ppi, 16 grayscale (or 7" Gallery 3 color on Page Color, $329)</li>
<li>OS: Android 13 with Google Play Store</li>
<li>RAM: 3 GB / Storage: 32 GB (expandable via microSD)</li>
<li>Battery: 2,300 mAh (about 4 weeks standby, 1 week reading)</li>
<li>Weight: 195 g</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Strengths:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Full Android app support</strong> &mdash; Kindle, Kobo, Libby, Pocket, Instapaper, Readwise Reader, even a terminal emulator or RSS reader &mdash; anything on Google Play runs on it</li>
<li>microSD slot means you can carry a 256 GB library of EPUBs without depending on cloud sync</li>
<li>Side-loaded Calibre integration via the official "Calibre Companion" app &mdash; push books from your computer over Wi-Fi</li>
<li>Boox's NeoReader handles EPUBs, PDFs, MOBI, AZW3, DJVU, CBR, CBZ, and DOCX natively</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Weaknesses:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Android on E-Ink is still sluggish &mdash; the app launcher and settings menus have a 200-400 ms lag compared to LCD Android phones</li>
<li>Google Play Services updates are 6-12 months behind Pixel phones, which occasionally causes app compatibility issues</li>
<li>No hardware page-turn button on the 7-inch models (only the larger Boox Note and Boox Max have it)</li>
<li>Battery life is "weeks" not "months" &mdash; closer to a phone than a Kindle</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Power users who want one E-Ink device that can run Kindle, Kobo, Libby, and Readwise all at once, with a microSD-loaded offline library. The Android flexibility is unmatched.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="kobo-libra-colour-the-reader-first-design">Kobo Libra Colour: The Reader-First Design</h2>
<p><a href="https://www.kobo.com/ca/en/ereaders/libra-colour">Kobo Libra Colour</a> launched in April 2024 but became widely available in 2025 and is the 2026 standard for "I just want to read books on a great E-Ink device." It runs Kobo's locked Linux-based firmware (no app store), but the native reader software is widely regarded as the best in the industry for EPUB and KEPUB files.</p>
<p><strong>Specifications:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Screen: 7" E-Ink Kaleido 3 color, 300 ppi (black-and-white) / 150 ppi (color)</li>
<li>OS: Kobo firmware (Linux, locked, but supports EPUB, KEPUB, PDF, MOBI, CBR, CBZ, HTML, RTF, TXT)</li>
<li>RAM: 1 GB / Storage: 32 GB</li>
<li>Battery: 2,050 mAh (up to 40 days reading, 100 days standby)</li>
<li>Weight: 199.5 g</li>
<li>Special: physical page-turn buttons + landscape mode</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Strengths:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Color E-Ink for covers, comics, and manga</strong> &mdash; Kaleido 3 is noticeably better than the Gallery 3 in Boox for color fidelity (150 ppi color is a real upgrade over dithered 300 ppi grayscale)</li>
<li><strong>Physical page-turn buttons</strong> &mdash; the asymmetrical design with the grip on the right side is the most ergonomic e-reader shape since the Kindle Oasis 3</li>
<li><strong>Pocket integration</strong> &mdash; save articles from any browser, sync to the Kobo over Wi-Fi, read on E-Ink later</li>
<li><strong>Dropbox and Google Drive support</strong> &mdash; sideload EPUBs by dropping them in a folder; no computer required</li>
<li>Battery life: 40 days of reading is real, not marketing</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Weaknesses:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>No app store &mdash; if you want Kindle, Libby, or Readwise, you need another device</li>
<li>Kobo's store is smaller than Amazon's (4 million titles vs Amazon's 12 million)</li>
<li>No note-taking or stylus support</li>
<li>1 GB of RAM means large PDFs (50+ MB) can lag during pinch-zoom</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Readers who want the best possible EPUB and manga reading experience, period. The combination of color, physical buttons, and 40-day battery is the "just read books" answer.</p>
<hr />
