<h2 id="faq">FAQ</h2>
<p><strong>Q: Can I read my Kindle library on the Kobo Libra Colour?</strong><br />A: Yes, via two methods. You can use Amazon's "Download &amp; Transfer via USB" to get DRM-free copies of books you own, then sideload via Dropbox or Google Drive. For a fully automated solution, the Calibre + DeDRM plugin combination works, but it requires stripping Amazon's DRM, which may violate Amazon's terms in some jurisdictions. Kobo's native store is the cleanest path if you don't already own Kindle books.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Does the Xteink X4 work with iPad or laptops?</strong><br />A: iPad support is limited &mdash; iPadOS does not support USB-C alt-mode external displays from accessories (it only supports external monitors via Stage Manager). For laptops, the X4 works with macOS Sonoma+ and Windows 11 as a secondary USB-C display, similar to a portable monitor. Linux support is experimental.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Can Boox run the Kindle app and sync my Kindle highlights?</strong><br />A: Yes. The Kindle Android app installs from Google Play on Boox devices and syncs your library, highlights, and reading position exactly like a phone or tablet. The reading experience is slightly slower than on a Kindle Paperwhite (page turns take 200-300 ms on Boox vs 80 ms on Paperwhite), but the convenience of having Kindle + Kobo + Libby on one device is a real win.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Is the Kobo Libra Colour's color screen noticeably worse than an iPad?</strong><br />A: Yes &mdash; Kaleido 3 color E-Ink renders at 150 ppi (vs 264 ppi on an iPad), so text and fine details are visibly softer. The color saturation is also about 30% of an LCD. But the trade-off is sunlight readability and 40-day battery life. For color content where you want to see a book's cover or a manga page's colors, it's good enough; for photo editing or video, it's not.</p>
<p><strong>Q: Which device is best for a first-time E-Ink buyer?</strong><br />A: The Kobo Libra Colour, for two reasons. First, the locked firmware means there's no learning curve &mdash; turn it on, sign in, buy or sideload a book, read. Second, the 40-day battery and physical buttons make it forgiving for someone who's never used an E-Ink device before. The X4 is an accessory, not a primary reader, and the Boox Page is for users who already know they want Android flexibility.</p>
<hr />
<h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion: Pick by Use Case, Not by Spec Sheet</h2>
<p>The three devices in this comparison are not direct competitors &mdash; they each solve a different secondary-screen problem. The Xteink X4 is a snap-on phone accessory for $179 that turns any MagSafe phone into an E-Ink reader. The Boox Page is a $259-$329 Android tablet that runs every reading app from Google Play and is the most flexible. The Kobo Libra Colour is a $219 locked reader that does one thing &mdash; reading books on E-Ink &mdash; better than any other device at this price.</p>
<p><strong>Decision tree:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>You already have a Kindle / Kobo / Libby app you love &rarr; <strong>Boox Page</strong></li>
<li>You want the best possible "just a reader" experience &rarr; <strong>Kobo Libra Colour</strong></li>
<li>You want a snap-on accessory, not a separate device &rarr; <strong>Xteink X4</strong></li>
<li>You read manga or color comics &rarr; <strong>Kobo Libra Colour</strong> (Kaleido 3 is the best color here)</li>
<li>You take handwritten notes &rarr; <strong>Boox Go 7</strong> (only option with a stylus)</li>
<li>You carry a 200+ GB offline library &rarr; <strong>Boox Page</strong> (microSD slot)</li>
</ul>
<p>If you want to optimize your existing EPUB library for any of these screens, the <code>ebook-convert</code> commands above will cut reflow glitches and improve line length. The same EPUB file usually renders 30% better with the right <code>--output-profile</code> and margin settings.</p>
